            <fr:title text="CISC vs RISC">CISC vs RISC</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Two design philosophies for an instruction set architecture.</html:p><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/RIS1/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>RIS1</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/RIS1/</fr:route><fr:title text="Complex instruction set computing (CISC)">Complex instruction set computing (CISC)</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>An ISA with many specialized instructions, including ones that combine memory access with arithmetic or operate on complex types (strings, decimal numbers). One instruction often does the work of several. x86 is the canonical example.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/XJQO/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>XJQO</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/XJQO/</fr:route><fr:title text="Reduced instruction set computing (RISC)">Reduced instruction set computing (RISC)</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>An ISA with a small set of simple, uniform instructions; explicit load and store; arithmetic only on registers. Each instruction does little but maps cleanly to hardware. PowerPC, MIPS, ARM are RISC.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(200, 55, 45, 0.85);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(200, 55, 45, 0.06);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(200, 55, 45, 0.85);">Problem.</html:span> <fr:link href="/RIS1/" title="Complex instruction set computing (CISC)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/RIS1/" display-uri="RIS1" type="local">CISC</fr:link> needs a fat <fr:link href="/87GH/" title="Microarchitecture" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/87GH/" display-uri="87GH" type="local">Microarchitecture</fr:link> engine to translate its complex instructions into hardware-executable primitives. That's silicon area, power, and design complexity that doesn't directly add throughput.</html:div>

 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(40, 150, 80, 0.9);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(40, 150, 80, 0.06);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(40, 150, 80, 0.9);">Solution.</html:span> Once <fr:link href="/XJQO/" title="Reduced instruction set computing (RISC)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/XJQO/" display-uri="XJQO" type="local">RISC</fr:link> clearly won as a hardware model, x86 vendors adopted <html:em>instruction translation</html:em>: a <fr:link href="/RIS1/" title="Complex instruction set computing (CISC)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/RIS1/" display-uri="RIS1" type="local">CISC</fr:link> front-end decodes x86 into RISC-like <fr:link href="/WEW2/" title="Micro-operations" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/WEW2/" display-uri="WEW2" type="local">Micro-operations</fr:link> internally. The chip is <fr:link href="/XJQO/" title="Reduced instruction set computing (RISC)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/XJQO/" display-uri="XJQO" type="local">RISC</fr:link> on the inside, <fr:link href="/RIS1/" title="Complex instruction set computing (CISC)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/RIS1/" display-uri="RIS1" type="local">CISC</fr:link> on the outside.</html:div>

 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);">Remark.</html:span> The cost of legacy is real. The original Pentium spent roughly 30% of its transistors on legacy support (mostly the microcode ROM). The Pentium Pro spent 40% on backward compatibility. Modern x86 chips have absorbed this overhead because they can — transistor budgets grew faster than the legacy tax.</html:div>
</fr:mainmatter>
